Time, solar phase (degrees), and Earth's longitudinal (in degrees) all increase at a constant rate with periodic resets down to 0 for solar phase and Earth longitudinal (which makes sense as periodic measurements are being taken by a satellite orbiting at a constant velocity). The number of particles per 100 ms has a lot of signal contamination and additionally seems to jump upwards every so often (approximately avery 54,000 data points). The background pdf might have to be built with signals nearby the point we're curious about, or generated from a bunch of folded sections of the data. The background pdf also might be approximatable through a Poisson distribution (since it's a bunch of independent events) changing as a decaying exponential folded over a factor of 54,000.

Part 2) The background is not consistent across the dataset. Find and describe as accurately as you can how the background changes.¶

The background jumps up by around 7-8 particles per 100ms then slowly decreases exponentially-ish to where it began over the course of almost 50,000 measurements

Part 3) Create a model for the background that includes time dependence, and explicitly compare your model to the data. How good is your model of the background?¶

My model (shown below) appears decently similar to the actual data (shown below my model), as both have a repeating cycle starting at around 42,000 every 54,000 data points where the data jumps up to mostly range between 2 and 22, then decays to mostly range between 14 and 0 before repeating the cycle once again. One problem with my model is that it tends to have a few more outliers than the actual data, and so it might be more difficult to identify outliers in the actual data.

In [10]:
# Generated Model Code
from scipy.stats import poisson

start_point = 0
num_points = 100000

x = np.linspace(start_point,start_point+num_points,num_points)
mu = 4 + 7 ** (1-(((x+12000)%54000)/54000))
pois = poisson.rvs(mu, size=num_points, loc = 0)

plt.scatter(np.linspace(start_point,start_point+num_points,num_points),pois[start_point:start_point+num_points])
plt.title("Generated Model for Particle Counts Per 100 ms")
plt.xlabel("Measurement Number")
plt.ylabel("Generated Particle Count in 100 ms Window")

Part 4) Because the background varies, your discovery sensitivity threshold (how many particles you would need to see) also varies. What is the '5-sigma' threshold for a 100 millisecond GRB at different times?¶

In [13]:
# Calculations for the discovery sensitivity threshold in number of particles
from scipy.stats import norm

start_point = 0
num_points = 100000

x = np.linspace(start_point,start_point+num_points,num_points)
mu_arr = 4 + 7 ** (1-(((x+12000)%54000)/54000))

print("Following 5-sigma threshold units are in number of particles")
print("5-sigma threshold for a 100ms GRB at 0th measurement: " + str(poisson.ppf(norm.cdf(5), mu = mu_arr[0])))
print("5-sigma threshold for a 100ms GRB at 10000th measurement: " + str(poisson.ppf(norm.cdf(5), mu = mu_arr[10000])))
print("5-sigma threshold for a 100ms GRB at 20000th measurement: " + str(poisson.ppf(norm.cdf(5), mu = mu_arr[20000])))
print("5-sigma threshold for a 100ms GRB at 30000th measurement: " + str(poisson.ppf(norm.cdf(5), mu = mu_arr[30000])))
print("5-sigma threshold for a 100ms GRB at 40000th measurement: " + str(poisson.ppf(norm.cdf(5), mu = mu_arr[40000])))
print("5-sigma threshold for a 100ms GRB at 50000th measurement: " + str(poisson.ppf(norm.cdf(5), mu = mu_arr[50000])))

Part 3) Using your background distribution, hunt for your signal (either faint stars, or a transient). Describe what you find.¶

Plan is to average the images together and then find locations that are consistently over a 5-sigma value. This will catch brighter stars, but if wanted I can filter them out by discarding locations that are consistently over a 20 or 30 sigma value.

In [21]:
# Start with all 10 images averaged into a single 200 by 200 array
avg_images = np.mean(img_data,axis=2)
avg_images.reshape((200,200))

# Finds where average of images is over 5 standard deviations away from mean
bright_index = np.where(avg_images > std_dev * 5)

# Gets values where over 5 standard deviations away from mean
bright_val = avg_images[bright_index]

# Gets indices where under 30 standard deviations away from mean
# as well as over 5 standard deviations away from mean,
# ie removes bright stars to only leave faint stars
faint_index = np.where(bright_val < std_dev * 30)

# Gets values where under 30 standard deviations away from mean
# as well as over 5 standard deviations away from mean
faint_val = bright_val[faint_index]

# Gets indices of faint stars in original averaged array
faint_x = bright_index[0][faint_index]
faint_y = bright_index[1][faint_index]
faint_true_coordinates = np.append(faint_x, faint_y).reshape(2,56)

print("Number of faint stars: " + str(np.shape(faint_val)))
print("Values of faint stars: " + str(faint_val))

print("Values of faint star coordinates: " + str(faint_true_coordinates))

Part 4) You and your lab partner had different pdf(), but were using the same data. Explore why this is.¶

We were attempting to find different things from the data, ie I was looking to find consistent sources of light while my lab partner was trying to find a single bright transient in the data, so I averaged the images to better be able to see consistent sources while my lab partner likely tried to find differences between images to isolate the blip and distinguish it from more consistent sources of light.
